description: The original House of Secrets logo was designed by Gaspar Saladino. It first appeared in 1956 as the mystery - suspense anthology comic began its 80 issue run. The title retained features of other anthology series, such as one page public service announcements from prominent super heroes, occasional text pieces, and one-page filler gags. Although it had a fairly steady stable of writers and artists, including Jack Kirby - who wrote early tales such as, "The cats who knew too much" and "The hole in the sky" and also drew several of the series' early covers - it had some recurring characters, such as the super natural sleuth Mark Merlin and the super villain Eclipso. A number of early stories were later reprinted in "The Unexpected" in the late 1960s. Many stories would also be reprinted in a the resurrected "House of Secrets" which returned in the 1960s as a companion to a new version of the horror - mystery - suspense anthology, "House of Mystery." At that point, "House of Secrets" stories were narrated by Abel, whereas Cain hosted the stories in "House of Mystery" The Swamp Thing, the monster made from vegetative matter, made his first appearance on the cover of issue# 92 of the revamped House of Secrets in July 1971.
name: House of Secrets

description:
Showcase was a flagship title of DC's during the Golden and Silver Ages. It was here that many heroes had their origins told, including the Flash, Green Lantern, Adam Strange, The Atom, Metal Men and the Sea Devils, before going on to star in their own titles. Showcase #4 is widely regarded as being the first Silver Age Comic.

However, not all characters that starred in Showcase were completely new; Lois Lane, Aquaman and Tommy Tomorrow were all cover stars for this title. Showcase also had licensed characters, such as G.I. Joe and James Bond.

Although canceled for a time in the early 1970s, it was revived a few years later as part of the marketing campaign for DC Comics known as the DC Explosion. It was subsequently cancelled in a wave of cancellations by DC which came to be known as the DC Implosion. Issues 105 and 106 were later published elsewhere.

description:
G.I. Combat is a comic book anthology of stories about American soldiers during World War II, the Korean War, the Vietnam War and the Cold War. The series was originally published by Quality Comics. After DC bought Quality Comics in 1956, G.I. Combat was one of the few comics they decided to keep. They continued the series until 1987, making it one of the last long-running war comics to come to an end.

One of the most prominent features of G.I. Combat is the Haunted Tank, a crew of soldiers led by Jeb Stuart and the ghost of a deceased Confederate General only he can see.

#1-43: Quality Comics

#44-288: DC Comics

Issues #211-225 are published by Dell.
name: Tip Top Comics

description:
Harvey's last try at Code approved watered down "horror."

Alarming tales is made up almost entirely of stories taken from previous pre-code Harvey horror comics, only they have been altered, with new dialog in the word balloons and some new art so as to no longer offend the Comic Book Code of Approval.

For instance, in one called Clean as a Whistle which first appeared in Black Cat 49, a husband kills his domineering and cleanliness obsessed wife by filling her bath tub with acid.

In the altered version that appears in issue 5 the text changes the wife to his sister, and the last half of the last page is changed so that instead of murdering her, he steals all her furniture and everything else in her apartment leaving it clean as a whistle.

There were also some new stories as well.
name: Alarming Tales
